Technical Information

Artificial intelligence

In computer science, artificial intelligence AI , sometimes called machine intelligence, is intelligence demonstrated by machines, in contrast to the natural intelligence displayed by humans and animals. Computer science defines AI research as the study of "intelligent agents": any device that perceives its environment and takes actions that maximize its chance of successfully achieving its goals. Colloquially, the term "artificial intelligence" is used to describe machines that mimic "cognitive" functions that humans associate with other human minds, such as "learning " and "problem solving " As machines become increasingly capable, tasks considered to require "intelligence" are often removed from the definition of AI, a phenomenon known as the AI effect. A quip in Tesler's Theorem says "AI is whatever hasn't been done yet. " For instance, optical character recognition is frequently excluded

from things considered to be AI, having become a routine technology. Modern machine capabilities generally classified as AI include successfully understanding human speech, competing at the highest level in strategic game systems (such as chess and Go), autonomously operating cars, intelligent routing in content delivery networks, and military simulations.

defination of robotic

Robotics or Human-Robot is the bundle of science and technologies that interested in studying, designing, developing and manufacturing robots. Robotics science is concerned with electronics science, mechanics and computer programming, as well as computer systems for their control,

sensory responses, and information processing. These techniques deal with automatic machines that can replace humans in hazardous environments or manufacturing processes, or resemble humans in appearance, behavior, and/or perception. Many robots today are inspired by their nature to contribute to the field of biologically inspired robots.

The concept of creating machines that can operate independently dates back to classical times, but research on the functions and potential uses of robots did not grow significantly until the 20th century. Throughout history, robots have often been seen as simulators of human behavior and often manage tasks in a similar way. Today, robots are a rapidly growing field, with continued technological advancements, research, design, and construction of new robots serving different practical purposes, whether locally, commercially, or militarily. Many robots perform functions that pose a threat to people such as defusing bombs, mines and exploring shipwrecks.

In order to look at robots as an application of the principles of motion with engines to provide motion and sensing to provide space and speed may miss the inherent complexity of the discipline. The real robot does not face the possibility of errors due to a number of reasons, of which incorrect data (e.g. mass, the direction, and the distance), friction forces and terrain estimates, movement at joint joints, standard errors in sensors, and errors in reading values of sensors. The resulting errors in the actions of the robot need to be repaired; preferably, without any clear human help. These corrections cannot be calculated previously using the laws of physics and must be generated, and detected, through the robot where the process is performed to enhance its ability to avoid faults, absorbing performance degradation and even self-restoration. The necessary correction varies from one repetition of a process to another because of the unpredictability of many influences.

overview of robot

There is a debate between scientists and linguists alike about the precise definition of the robot. Some people select this description for every machine that can be controlled and moved remotely, while others do not agree with it. Their argument is that these machines, like the car or plane, It cannot be

considered a robot because it does not have the ability to think and make decisions on its own, and they provide an example that if the machine can act according to a predetermined program to move away from the two-step back and move to the right or left and continue to progress, This makes it possible to call it a real human.

. It is clear from this that the basic idea held by the authors of this view is that the real Robot, in the belief of some must possess artificial intelligence and have the ability to distinguish patterns and identify systems and reasoning and conclusion. Of which the digital micro-mirror device, first announced in 1987. His idea was to erect several thousand precision mirrors in the robot to respond to the image element, to add more flexibility in the movement and reaction.

There are many types of robots, including those used in the industrial sector, which are automatic devices can be adapted and reprogrammed, and moving on three axes or more, and use the majority of these robots in large industrial companies for the purpose of welding, dyeing, ironing, monitoring, transport objects, control the quality or validity of finished products, and used in the assembly of car parts in factories. These robots are usually programmed to perform their tasks quickly duplicate and accurate. The so-called computer vision of these robots was added during the early years of the first decade of the 21st century, which gave them a degree of autonomy and flexibility in carrying out programmed tasks by understanding and analyzing the images they receive on a computer installed inside.

There are types of robots is capable of movement and driving on its own, including a robot plane and self-controlled aircraft with artificial neural networks. The most prominent of these types are the two robots sent by the International Space Agency in 2004 to the surface of Mars. There are robots, which are able to regroup itself Semi-independently, such as reducing its size to pass through a narrow tunnel, and these robots contain in its model several links in addition to the CPU and the receivers and special memory, and these transmissions able to do some movements semi-obedient, due to it contain them On a flexible unit, either by converting compressed air energy in cylinders into linear or rotational motions, or by converting electrical energy into kinetic energy. And there is sophisticated methods have been developed to move the robots, there are also types of robots dedicated to doing housework, teach children and play chess. This type of robot is called social robot and has a high degree of independence. It is noted that the term social robot cannot be applied to a tool that is controlled by a human from afar. Social robot must succeed in "two main tests" to classify it as a social type:

Turing test: Is a test to see if the robotic system can be called an intelligent system. This test was developed by the British mathematician Alan Turing (1912-1954), is a dialogue with the robot. If the laboratory cannot confirm 100% that the answer was a human or a Robotic answer, the test considered successful.

Isaac Asimov Test: a test to demonstrate the commitment of the so-called robotic laws, and these laws are:

A robot may not injure a human being or, through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm.

A robot must obey the orders given it by human beings except where such orders would conflict with the First Law.

A robot must protect its own existence as long as such protection does not conflict with the First or Second Laws.

It is rare to design human-robots in the form of a complete human being, and it can be said that the human-robot is a device or machine that can replace man in some situations, and its external form depends on the task for which it was manufactured. The human body is a highly functional organic organ that can perform many functions.

It can carry out special tasks that may be boring, time-consuming or dangerous to human life. The human-robot is manufactured for limited works.

anatomy of robot

Sensors Part: Used to help the human-robot to sense the external influences, some of them are able to sense the heat while others feel pressure or rotation or inclination or electromagnetic sensors or light sensors of all kinds. Processor Part: Usually represents the brain of the human-robot.

It's not only the data processor but also the accompanying units of electronics and artificial memory, it gives the human-robot the ability to perform many functions, such as to define external styles or direct its movement, and can identify shapes. The structure of the processor varies according to the task of the human-robot. There are programmable processing units, such as FPGA and PLC modules, and there are specialized processors DSP and processors that have an operating system. In short, it is the part entrusted with the application of the various algorithms required by the robot in the performance of his mission. Each robot can have its own processor or several of them can be shared a central processor.

Motor Controller Part: The electrical power of the small human-robots ranges from 4.5 volts to 36 volts. If the voltages generated are higher than this limit, coolant devices should be installed in the relevant coil.

The Engine Part: The part responsible for the movement of the robot, and use electric motors and combustion engines to ensure the movement of these machines as accurate as possible. The energy used to move the robot varies by type and purpose, it may be aerobic or electronic energy or fluid power.

Communication Tools Part: An information exchange point between Android and the outside world. Some have the ability to produce frequencies with a frequency of up to 2.4 GHz. The robot can exchange information wirelessly or via wires using the GPIB and RS 232 protocols.

Software Part: Programs designed to control and control the movements of the robot and to make a series of movements and effects consistent or desired.

Batteries and Charging Device Part: Many robots have so-called batteries and chargers, such as solar cells attached to power transformers, and a small charger to recharge the battery.

The robot consists of electronic systems and sensitive devices that match the nervous system and sensory organs of human beings. The robot also has an electronic mind, an electronic calculator, and with the development of the use of electronic chips in the calculator, it has become possible to equip the robot with a strong electronic mind, and thus it can be programmed to perform complex operations. In fact, the evolution of this electronic mind has surpassed other robotic systems and has become highly operational.

Communication with the robot is difficult, and one of the electronic computing languages must be used to achieve this. In their experiments, robots Scientists benefit from a study of the similarities between communication and control systems in human beings and their machine counterparts. This section of science is known as cybernetic. This word was first invented by American mathematician Norbert Feiner in a book published in 1948. Scientists can resort to the rules of biological electronics when it is necessary to manufacture mechanical organs to plant in a human body in order to cure a certain disability. These organs can be considered as robotic members of a robot, not mechanical organs in the full sense of the word. The arms and the artificial hands, for example, are highly sensitive and respond spontaneously to the precise electrical pulses resulting from the constriction of normal human muscles.

Scientists are working on the invention of more prosthetic pieces and prostheses of the human body, such as the adjuster the pulse used to strengthen the human heart. Some say it is possible in the near future that doctors will be able to implant whole artificial hearts for those who need from heart patients. Others predict that by the end of the twenty-first century all parts of the human body will be replaced by an industrial one, and this may lead to the presence of quasi-human beings, such as those appearing in serials and science fiction films.

communication and contro

The communication and control devices inside the human-robot can be as complex as human organs, and therefore have the independent science to study them. These devices, which operate remotely, contain memory or sensory devices or work automatically, it must rely on a feedback system to

achieve self-control, as for communication and control devices are:

A phone with buttons, with limited memory to store repeated numbers, since the robot needs a comprehensive memory.

Sensitive devices that enable them to reach their goals. The robot needs a number of these devices to gather information about the surrounding environment.

Automatic temperature stabilizer keeps it at the same ambient temperature, turns off and operates automatically, according to information obtained from its sensitive devices.

Types of robots

The Robots can be divided according to their respective characteristics and the target for which they are prepared. The robot may be designed to perform a specific action with precision, or for a certain number of actions, but with less precision. Any robot can be reprogrammed to do a different

job or behave in a different way than it should if its central unit allows. For example, the function of the machine arm used in factories can be modified from metal cutting to assembly it, welding it, attachment it, loading it, or even to a recreational vehicle used by the visitors of the factory, while load and transport robots can only be modified to assemble printed electronic boards.

Research Robots

Although most robots today are used in factories or homes to perform certain tasks, such as services, many new types of robots are being developed in laboratories around the world. Most robotics research doesn't focus only on specific industrial tasks, but on new types of robots, alternative methods of design, and new ways of manufacturing them. It is expected that these new types of robots will be able to solve some real problems in the human world after they are completed.

Independent General Purpose Robots

Independent general purpose robots are robots capable of doing a number of tasks on their own. They can move automatically in their familiar areas without guidance from anyone, recharging themselves whenever they need to, interacting with electronic doors, elevators and other key tasks. These robots can be connected, such as computers, electronic networks, programs, and other accessories that increase their effectiveness and usefulness. These machines can recognize certain people or things, speak, provide companionship, monitor climate, and respond to alarms, move equipment, and other useful tasks. Robots of independent general goals may result in a set of actions at one time or each task at different times of the day. Some of these robots try to imitate humans and have similar similarities in their form, in this case, it called the Human shape.

Dimension Robots

These robots are used to perform tasks that humans cannot perform because of their danger, after the goal, or not being able to reach it in normal, familiar ways. These robots do not follow a series of movements that are coordinated in advance but are controlled by someone from a distance. It may be in a room corresponding to the person or in another country, even on a scale that is completely different from that of the operator. For example, a partial surgical robot enables a doctor to perform a procedure inside a patient's body on a very small scale compared to manual surgery, that's short the healing clearly time. Other examples of these machines are the bombs used to dismantle the bombs, where the explosives expert sends the robot to the bomb site and disassembles it, and there are also many writers who use a device called the "long pen" to sign their works from a distance. Unmanned drones are another prime example, and their use is increasingly being used by various armies of the world where they are used to survey sites and shoot targets. The US military uses hundreds of robots, such as the IOB robot's portable bot, and the Foster-Miller Filler, both in Iraq and Afghanistan to dismantle roadside bombs or unexploded ordnance. This activity is called "explosive ordnance disposal.
